---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import siteData from '../data/site.json';

const page = siteData.pages.about;
const styles = [
  'assets/css/tokens.css',
  'assets/css/interior-base.css',
  'assets/css/layout.css',
  'assets/css/components.css',
  'assets/css/mission.css',
];
---
<Base
  title={page.title}
  description={page.description}
  canonical={page.canonical}
  subtitle={page.subtitle}
  eyebrow={page.eyebrow}
  introKicker={page.introKicker}
  introTitle={page.introTitle}
  introText={page.introText}
  currentNav={page.currentNav}
  styles={styles}
>
  <section class="card mission-copy">
    <p>Saint Expedite is the patron of urgent causes, the saint invoked when it cannot wait. He is the figure called on when the proper channels have failed, when the institutions are too slow, when the paperwork would arrive after the opportunity is gone. The press takes his name and his economy.</p>
    <p>Osiris was killed by Set, his body scattered in pieces across Egypt. Isis gathered him back, limb by limb, and reconstituted him into something that could endure. The press takes the same disposition toward Southern writing: a tradition dispersed across neglect, commerce, and institutional indifference, waiting for someone willing to work outside the systems that scattered it.</p>
    <p>We publish from New Orleans. Three active arms: SEXP for original fiction and novella, the Library of the Southern Civilization for Southern reprints and archival work, and a European translation series across Spanish, French, and Russian. No board. No grants. No permissions required. The press answers to the work.</p>
  </section>

  <div class="mission-phase-grid">
    <section class="card mission-copy">
      <span class="phase-kicker">Phase one</span>
      <h3 class="phase-heading">A presence</h3>
      <p>A catalog, a channel, first books. The immediate project is proof: that something is here, that the work exists, that it can reach a reader directly without the institutional machinery of the trade press or the credentialing of the academic publisher.</p>
      <p>SEXP publishes original Southern fiction and novella. The Library of the Southern Civilization recovers Southern reprints and archival texts that deserve continued circulation. The translation series brings Spanish, French, and Russian works into English with no academic apparatus attached. Each title sold directly. Each dollar back to the press.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="card mission-copy">
      <span class="phase-kicker">Phase two</span>
      <h3 class="phase-heading">A magazine</h3>
      <p>A print journal for fiction, reprints, translation, and criticism. Not a literary magazine in the contemporary sense: no workshop aesthetics, no advertiser relationships, no editorial board constituted for appearances. A journal of record for the tradition the press is building.</p>
      <p>The argument for print is simple: digital publishing is disposable, and the journals that have lasted have always been objects. Sustained by the catalog. Distributed directly to subscribers and to the handful of bookshops that understand what it is.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="card mission-copy">
      <span class="phase-kicker">Phase three</span>
      <h3 class="phase-heading">A fellowship</h3>
      <p>A foundation mechanism for Southern writers outside the university and the grant system. The university has captured literary production in a way that would have been unrecognizable to the tradition the press is interested in. The fellowship funds time and the space to work, without application committees, without residency programs built around networking, without the soft requirement that the work conform to what the institution will certify.</p>
      <p>Self-sustaining through the press's own economics. The catalog funds the magazine. The magazine and the catalog together fund the fellowship. No external dependency. No institutional approval required at any stage.</p>
    </section>
  </div>

  <section class="card mission-copy">
    <p class="mission-ethos">Zero guardrails. Non-institutional. Post-corporate.</p>
    <p>The press operates past the approval structures of literary commerce. Not in opposition to them, because opposition still requires acknowledgment. Past them.</p>
    <p>There is no editorial board and no advisory committee. There are no acquisitions meetings and no sensitivity review. There is a press, a body of work, and a conviction that Southern writing at its formal and spiritual extremity is among the most serious literature in the English language, and has been systematically underserved by the institutions that claim to represent it.</p>
    <p>The work either earns its existence or it does not. There is no other standard.</p>
  </section>

  <Fragment slot="scripts">
    <script is:inline src="/assets/js/site-shell.js" type="module"></script>
  </Fragment>
</Base>
